# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: path-tracing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The **bidirectional reflectance distribution function** (**BRDF**), symbol $f_{\text{r}}(\omega _{\text{i}},\,\omega _{\text{r}})$ , is a function of four real variables that defines how light from a source is reflected off an opaque surface.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] It is employed in the optics of real-world light, in computer graphics algorithms, and in computer vision algorithms.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] Each direction $\omega$ is itself parameterized by azimuth angle $\phi$ and zenith angle $\theta$ , therefore the BRDF as a whole is a function of 4 variables.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The BRDF has units sr−1, with steradians (sr) being a unit of solid angle.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The BRDF was first defined by Fred Nicodemus around 1965.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] where L is radiance, or power per unit solid-angle-in-the-direction-of-a-ray per unit projected-area-perpendicular-to-the-ray, E is irradiance, or power per unit *surface area*, and $\theta _{\text{i}}$ is the angle between $\omega _{\text{i}}$ and the surface normal, $\mathbf {n}$ .
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The index ${\text{i}}$ indicates incident light, whereas the index ${\text{r}}$ indicates reflected light.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The **Spatially Varying Bidirectional Reflectance Distribution Function** (SVBRDF) is a 6-dimensional function, $f_{\text{r}}(\omega _{\text{i}},\,\omega _{\text{r}},\,\mathbf {x} )$ , where $\mathbf {x}$ describes a 2D location over an object's surface.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The **Bidirectional Texture Function** (BTF) is appropriate for modeling non-flat surfaces, and has the same parameterization as the SVBRDF; however in contrast, the BTF includes non-local scattering effects like shadowing, masking, interreflections or subsurface scattering.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The functions defined by the BTF at each point on the surface are thus called **Apparent BRDFs**.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] In all these cases, the dependence on the wavelength of light has been ignored.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] In reality, the BRDF is wavelength dependent, and to account for effects such as iridescence or luminescence the dependence on wavelength must be made explicit: $f_{\text{r}}(\lambda _{\text{i}},\,\omega _{\text{i}},\,\lambda _{\text{r}},\,\omega _{\text{r}})$ .
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] In this case it can be parameterized as $f_{\text{r}}(\lambda ,\,\omega _{\text{i}},\,\omega _{\text{r}})$ , with only one wavelength parameter.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The BRDF is a fundamental radiometric concept, and accordingly is used in computer graphics for photorealistic rendering of synthetic scenes (see the rendering equation), as well as in computer vision for many inverse problems such as object recognition.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] BRDF has also been used for modeling light trapping in solar cells (e.g. using the OPTOS formalism) or low concentration solar photovoltaic systems.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] In the context of satellite remote sensing, NASA uses a BRDF model to characterise surface reflectance anisotropy.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] For a given land area, the BRDF is established based on selected multiangular observations of surface reflectance.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] While single observations depend on view geometry and solar angle, the MODIS BRDF/Albedo product describes intrinsic surface properties in several spectral bands, at a resolution of 500 meters.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The BRDF/Albedo product can be used to model surface albedo depending on atmospheric scattering.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] BRDFs can be measured directly from real objects using calibrated cameras and lightsources; however, many phenomenological and analytic models have been proposed including the Lambertian reflectance model frequently assumed in computer graphics.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] Matusik et al. found that interpolating between measured samples produced realistic results and was easy to understand.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] Three elemental components that can be used to model a variety of light-surface interactions.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The incoming light ray is shown in black, the reflected ray(s) modeled by the BRDF in gray.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] Traditionally, BRDF measurement devices called gonioreflectometers employ one or more goniometric arms to position a light source and a detector at various directions from a flat sample of the material to be measured.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] To measure a full BRDF, this process must be repeated many times, moving the light source each time to measure a different incidence angle.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] Unfortunately, using such a device to densely measure the BRDF is very time-consuming.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] One of the first improvements on these techniques used a half-silvered mirror and a digital camera to take many BRDF samples of a planar target at once.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] Since this work, many researchers have developed other devices for efficiently acquiring BRDFs from real world samples, and it remains an active area of research.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] There is an alternative way to measure BRDF based on HDR images.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The standard algorithm is to measure the BRDF point cloud from images and optimize it by one of the BRDF models.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] A fast way to measure BRDF or BTDF is a conoscopic scatterometer The advantage of this measurement instrument is that a near-hemispheric measurement can be captured in a fraction of a second with resolution of roughly 0.1°.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The first is that the dynamic range is limited by the camera being used; this can be as low as 8 bits for older image sensors or as high as 32 bits for the newer automotive image sensors.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] The other disadvantage is that for BRDF measurements the beam must pass from an external light source, bounce off a pellicle and pass in reverse through the first few elements of the conoscope before being scattered by the sample.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] Each of these elements is antireflection-coated, but roughly 0.3% of the light is reflected at each air-glass interface.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] These reflections will show up in the image as a spurious signal.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] For scattering surfaces with a large signal, this is not a problem, but for Lambertian surfaces it is.
[src:path-tracing/bidirectional-reflectance-distribution-function] BRDF fabrication refers to the process of implementing a surface based on the measured or synthesized information of a target BRDF.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Let $X\colon \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ be a random variable in some probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},\mathbb {P} )$ .
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] We wish to estimate the expected value of X under $\mathbb {P}$ , denoted $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ .
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] The basic idea of importance sampling is to sample from a different distribution to lower the variance of the estimation of $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ , or when sampling directly from $\mathbb {P}$ is difficult.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] This is accomplished by first choosing a random variable $Y\geq 0$ such that $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[Y]=1$ and that $\mathbb {P}$ -almost everywhere $Y(\omega )\neq 0$ .
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] When X is of constant sign over $\Omega$ , the best variable Y would clearly be $Y^{*}={\frac {X}{\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]}}\geq 0$ , so that $X/Y^{*}$ is the searched constant $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ and a single sample under $\mathbb {Q} ^{*}$ suffices to give its value.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Unfortunately we cannot take that choice, because $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ is precisely the value we are looking for!
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] therefore, a good probability change $\mathbb {Q}$ in importance sampling will redistribute the law of X so that its samples' frequencies are sorted directly according to their contributions in $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ as opposed to $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[1]$ .
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Importance sampling is often used as a Monte Carlo integrator.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] When $\mathbb {P}$ is the uniform distribution over $\Omega =\mathbb {R}$ , the expectation $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ corresponds to the integral of the real function $X\colon \mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Such methods are frequently used to estimate posterior densities or expectations in state and/or parameter estimation problems in probabilistic models that are too hard to treat analytically.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Examples include Bayesian networks and importance weighted variational autoencoders.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] The fundamental issue in implementing importance sampling simulation is the choice of the biased distribution which encourages the important regions of the input variables.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Choosing or designing a good biased distribution is the "art" of importance sampling.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] The rewards for a good distribution can be huge run-time savings; the penalty for a bad distribution can be longer run times than for a general Monte Carlo simulation without importance sampling.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Consider X to be the sample and ${\frac {f(X)}{g(X)}}$ to be the likelihood ratio, where f is the probability density (mass) function of the desired distribution and g is the probability density (mass) function of the biased/proposal/sample distribution.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Notice that when $X\geq 0$ , this variance becomes 0.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Consider estimating by simulation the probability $p_{t}\,$ of an event $X\geq t$ , where X is a random variable with cumulative distribution function $F(x)$ and probability density function $f(x)=F'(x)\,$ , where prime denotes derivative.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] A K -length independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) sequence $X_{i}\,$ is generated from the distribution F , and the number $k_{t}$ of random variables that lie above the threshold t are counted.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Note that the variance is low if $p_{t}\approx 1$ .
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Importance sampling is concerned with the determination and use of an alternate density function $f_{*}\,$ (for X ), usually referred to as a biasing density, for the simulation experiment.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] This density allows the event ${X\geq t\ }$ to occur more frequently, so the sequence lengths K gets smaller for a given estimator variance.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Alternatively, for a given K , use of the biasing density results in a variance smaller than that of the conventional Monte Carlo estimate.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] From the definition of $p_{t}\,$ , we can introduce $f_{*}\,$ as below.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] is a likelihood ratio and is referred to as the weighting function.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] This is the importance sampling estimator of $p_{t}\,$ and is unbiased.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] That is, the estimation procedure is to generate i.i.d. samples from $f_{*}\,$ and for each sample which exceeds $t\,$ , the estimate is incremented by the weight $W\,$ evaluated at the sample value.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] The results are averaged over $K\,$ trials.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Now, the importance sampling problem then focuses on finding a biasing density $f_{*}\,$ such that the variance of the importance sampling estimator is less than the variance of the general Monte Carlo estimate.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] For some biasing density function, which minimizes the variance, and under certain conditions reduces it to zero, it is called an optimal biasing density function.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Although there are many kinds of biasing methods, the following two methods are most widely used in the applications of importance sampling.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Shifting probability mass into the event region ${X\geq t\ }$ by positive scaling of the random variable $X\,$ with a number greater than unity has the effect of increasing the variance (mean also) of the density function.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] This results in a heavier tail of the density, leading to an increase in the event probability.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Scaling is probably one of the earliest biasing methods known and has been extensively used in practice.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] It is simple to implement and usually provides conservative simulation gains as compared to other methods.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] In importance sampling by scaling, the simulation density is chosen as the density function of the scaled random variable $aX\,$ , where usually $a>1$ for tail probability estimation.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] While scaling shifts probability mass into the desired event region, it also pushes mass into the complementary region $X<t\,$ which is undesirable.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] If $X\,$ is a sum of $n\,$ random variables, the spreading of mass takes place in an $n\,$ dimensional space.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] The consequence of this is a decreasing importance sampling gain for increasing $n\,$ , and is called the dimensionality effect.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] A modern version of importance sampling by scaling is e.g. so-called sigma-scaled sampling (SSS) which is running multiple Monte Carlo (MC) analysis with different scaling factors.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] In opposite to many other high yield estimation methods (like worst-case distances WCD) SSS does not suffer much from the dimensionality problem.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Also addressing multiple MC outputs causes no degradation in efficiency.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] On the other hand, as WCD, SSS is only designed for Gaussian statistical variables, and in opposite to WCD, the SSS method is not designed to provide accurate statistical corners.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Another SSS disadvantage is that the MC runs with large scale factors may become difficult, e. g. due to model and simulator convergence problems.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] In addition, in SSS we face a strong bias-variance trade-off: Using large scale factors, we obtain quite stable yield results, but the larger the scale factors, the larger the bias error.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] If the advantages of SSS does not matter much in the application of interest, then often other methods are more efficient.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Another simple and effective biasing technique employs translation of the density function (and hence random variable) to place much of its probability mass in the rare event region.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Translation does not suffer from a dimensionality effect and has been successfully used in several applications relating to simulation of digital communication systems.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] It often provides better simulation gains than scaling.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] where $c\,$ is the amount of shift and is to be chosen to minimize the variance of the importance sampling estimator.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] The fundamental problem with importance sampling is that designing good biased distributions becomes more complicated as the system complexity increases.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Complex systems are the systems with long memory since complex processing of a few inputs is much easier to handle.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] In principle, the importance sampling ideas remain the same in these situations, but the design becomes much harder.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] A successful approach to combat this problem is essentially breaking down a simulation into several smaller, more sharply defined subproblems.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Then importance sampling strategies are used to target each of the simpler subproblems.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Examples of techniques to break the simulation down are conditioning and error-event simulation (EES) and regenerative simulation.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] In order to identify successful importance sampling techniques, it is useful to be able to quantify the run-time savings due to the use of the importance sampling approach.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] The performance measure commonly used is $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ , and this can be interpreted as the speed-up factor by which the importance sampling estimator achieves the same precision as the MC estimator.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] This has to be computed empirically since the estimator variances are not likely to be analytically possible when their mean is intractable.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Other useful concepts in quantifying an importance sampling estimator are the variance bounds and the notion of asymptotic efficiency.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] One related measure is the so-called **Effective Sample Size** **(ESS)**.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Variance is not the only possible cost function for a simulation, and other cost functions, such as the mean absolute deviation, are used in various statistical applications.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Nevertheless, the variance is the primary cost function addressed in the literature, probably due to the use of variances in confidence intervals and in the performance measure $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ .
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] An associated issue is the fact that the ratio $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ overestimates the run-time savings due to importance sampling since it does not include the extra computing time required to compute the weight function.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Hence, some people evaluate the net run-time improvement by various means.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Perhaps a more serious overhead to importance sampling is the time taken to devise and program the technique and analytically derive the desired weight function.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] When different proposal distributions, $g_{i}(x)$ , $i=1,\ldots ,n,$ are jointly used for drawing the samples $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n},$ different proper weighting functions can be employed (e.g., see ).
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] In an adaptive setting, the proposal distributions, $g_{i,t}(x)$ , $i=1,\ldots ,n,$ and $t=1,\ldots ,T,$ are updated each iteration t of the adaptive importance sampling algorithm.
[src:path-tracing/importance-sampling] Hence, since a population of proposal densities is used, several suitable combinations of sampling and weighting schemes can be employed.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and non-uniform random variate generation, available for modeling phenomena with significant input uncertainties, e.g. risk assessments for nuclear power plants.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simulations.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] They can provide approximate solutions to problems too complex for mathematical analysis.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The name comes from the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, where the primary developer of the method, mathematician Stanisław Ulam, was inspired by his uncle's gambling habits.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, engineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] They have also been applied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political science.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scientific and technological breakthroughs.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the curse of dimensionality, the reliability of random number generators, and the verification and validation of the results.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Generate inputs randomly from a probability distribution over the domain.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Perform a deterministic computation of the outputs.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] For example, consider a quadrant (circular sector) inscribed in a unit square.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Uniformly scatter a given number of points over the square.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance from the origin of less than 1.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate of the ratio of the two areas, ⁠π/4⁠.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes the quadrant.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it falls within the quadrant.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Aggregating the results yields our final result, the approximation of π.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the whole square.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and their use benefitted greatly from pseudorandom number generators, which are far quicker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously employed.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often used in physical and mathematical problems and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other approaches.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probability distribution.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs such as the calculation of risk in business and, in mathematics, evaluation of multidimensional definite integrals with complicated boundary conditions.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In application to systems engineering problems (space, oil exploration, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo–based predictions of failure, cost overruns and schedule overruns are routinely better than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem having a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] By the law of large numbers, integrals described by the expected value of some random variable can be approximated by taking the empirical mean (a.k.a. the 'sample mean') of independent samples of the variable.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] When the probability distribution of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The central idea is to design a judicious Markov chain model with a prescribed stationary probability distribution.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] That is, in the limit, the samples being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (target) distribution.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] By the ergodic theorem, the stationary distribution is approximated by the empirical measures of the random states of the MCMC sampler.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] These flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the distributions of the random states of a Markov process whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the current random states (see McKean–Vlasov processes, nonlinear filtering equation).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In other instances, a flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann–Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, and many others).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinear Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing in the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by the sampled empirical measures.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In contrast with traditional Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these mean-field particle techniques rely on sequential interacting samples.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The terminology *mean field* reflects the fact that each of the *samples* (a.k.a. particles, individuals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empirical measures of the process.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] When the size of the system tends to infinity, these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical interaction between particles vanishes.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Suppose one wants to know the expected value $\mu$ of a population (and knows that $\mu$ exists), but does not have a formula available to compute it.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The simple Monte Carlo method gives an estimate for $\mu$ by running n simulations and averaging the simulations' results.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] It has no restrictions on the probability distribution of the inputs to the simulations, requiring only that the inputs are randomly generated and are independent of each other and that $\mu$ exists.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A sufficiently large n will produce a value for m that is arbitrarily close to $\mu$ ; more formally, it will be the case that, for any $\epsilon >0$ , $|\mu -m|\leq \epsilon$ .
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Suppose we want to know how many times we should expect to throw three eight-sided dice for the total of the dice throws to be at least T .
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The dice throws are randomly distributed and independent of each other.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] If n is large enough, m will be within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Choose the desired confidence level – the percent chance that, when the Monte Carlo algorithm completes, m is indeed within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Let z be the z -score corresponding to that confidence level.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Let $s^{2}$ be the estimated variance, sometimes called the "sample" variance; it is the variance of the results obtained from a relatively small number k of "sample" simulations.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Note that, when the algorithm completes, $m_{k}$ is the mean of the k results.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] If $n\leq k$ , then $m_{k}=m$ ; sufficient sample simulations were done to ensure that $m_{k}$ is within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] An alternative formula can be used in the special case where all simulation results are bounded above and below.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Choose a value for $\epsilon$ that is twice the maximum allowed difference between $\mu$ and m .
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Let $0<\delta <100$ be the desired confidence level, expressed as a percentage.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Let every simulation result $r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{i},\ldots ,r_{n}$ be such that $a\leq r_{i}\leq b$ for finite a and b .
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cost associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In general the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which may incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a single sample is high.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, the embarrassingly parallel nature of the algorithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) through parallel computing strategies in local processors, clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previously understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to estimate uncertainties in the simulations.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations invert this approach, solving deterministic problems using probabilistic metaheuristics (see simulated annealing).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the Buffon's needle problem, in which π can be estimated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi first experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In the late 1940s, Stanisław Ulam invented the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was working on nuclear weapons projects at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclear weapon.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A colleague of von Neumann and Ulam, Nicholas Metropolis, suggested using the name *Monte Carlo*, which refers to the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to gamble.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods were central to the simulations required for further postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Von Neumann, Nicholas Metropolis and others programmed the ENIAC computer to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a fission weapon core, in the spring of 1948.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at Los Alamos for the development of the hydrogen bomb, and became popularized in the fields of physics, physical chemistry, and operations research.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Air Force were two of the major organizations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Carlo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in many different fields.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carlo methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of Henry P.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] McKean Jr. on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parabolic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] An earlier pioneering article by Theodore E.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Harris and Herman Kahn, published in 1951, used mean-field genetic-type Monte Carlo methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologies are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. metaheuristic) in evolutionary computing.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The origins of these mean-field computational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of Alan Turing on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of Feynman–Kac path integrals.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The use of sequential Monte Carlo in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] It was in 1993, that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work the first application of a Monte Carlo resampling algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the system.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on a related "Monte Carlo filter", and the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989–1992 by P.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechanism.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines and Terry Lyons, and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral and Terry Lyons.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] There is no consensus on how *Monte Carlo* should be defined.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] For example, Ripley defines most probabilistic modeling as *stochastic simulation*, with *Monte Carlo* being reserved for Monte Carlo integration and Monte Carlo statistical tests.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Sawilowsky distinguishes between a simulation, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a technique that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical properties of some phenomena.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Kalos and Whitlock point out that such distinctions are not always easy to maintain.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stochastic process.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneously as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sampling." Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the Gelman-Rubin statistic.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results of these experiments are not well known.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown parameters, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation methods do not always require truly random numbers to be useful (although, for some applications such as primality testing, unpredictability is vital).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, pseudorandom sequences, making it easy to test and re-run simulations.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The only quality usually necessary to make good simulations is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a certain sense.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] What this means depends on the application, but typically they should pass a series of statistical tests.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Testing that the numbers are uniformly distributed or follow another desired distribution when a large enough number of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and most common ones.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Weak correlations between successive samples are also often desirable/necessary.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Pseudo-random number sampling algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a given probability distribution.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Low-discrepancy sequences are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Methods based on their use are called quasi-Monte Carlo methods.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] No statistically significant difference was found between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and RDRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 107 random numbers.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carlo simulations – for example, deterministic modeling using single-point estimates.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best guess" estimate.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for each input variable are chosen and the results recorded.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a probability distribution for each variable to produce hundreds or thousands of possible outcomes.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The results are analyzed to get probabilities of different outcomes occurring.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] This is because the "what if" analysis gives equal weight to all scenarios (see quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance), while the Monte Carlo method hardly samples in the very low probability regions.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The samples in such regions are called "rare events".
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs and systems with many coupled degrees of freedom.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In statistical physics, Monte Carlo molecular modeling is an alternative to computational molecular dynamics, and Monte Carlo methods are used to compute statistical field theories of simple particle and polymer systems.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo methods solve the many-body problem for quantum systems.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In radiation materials science, the binary collision approximation for simulating ion implantation is usually based on a Monte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In experimental particle physics, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing detectors, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In astrophysics, they are used in such diverse manners as to model both galaxy evolution and microwave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in the ensemble models that form the basis of modern weather forecasting.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for sensitivity analysis and quantitative probabilistic analysis in process design.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The need arises from the interactive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change relies on Monte Carlo methods in probability density function analysis of radiative forcing.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of computational biology, for example for Bayesian inference in phylogeny, or for studying biological systems such as genomes, proteins, or membranes.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or *ab initio* frameworks depending on the desired accuracy.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particular molecule to see if some chemical reaction is happening for instance.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical experiment, thought experiments can be conducted, e.g. breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing the local/global structure, or introducing external fields.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Path tracing, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Repeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of the samples to converge on the correct solution of the rendering equation, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics rendering methods in existence.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawilowsky.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] To provide implementations of hypothesis tests that are more efficient than exact tests such as permutation tests (which are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critical values for asymptotic distributions.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in Bayesian inference.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] This sample then approximates and summarizes all the essential features of the posterior.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the negative log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of the Fisher information matrix.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomization and permutation tests.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] An approximate randomization test is based on a specified subset of all permutations (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations have been considered).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified number of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if a permutation is drawn twice—or more frequently—for the efficiency of not having to track which permutations have already been selected).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called Monte-Carlo tree search that is useful for searching for the best move in a game.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Possible moves are organized in a search tree and many random simulations are used to estimate the long-term potential of each move.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A black box simulator represents the opponent's moves.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Play a simulated game starting with that node.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ancestors.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the value of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully corresponding to whether or not that node represents a good move.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games such as Go, Tantrix, Battleship, Havannah, and Arimaa.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The US Coast Guard utilizes Monte Carlo methods within its computer modeling software SAROPS in order to calculate the probable locations of vessels during search and rescue operations.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Each simulation can generate as many as ten thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided variables.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Search patterns are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to optimize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detection (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Ultimately this serves as a practical application of probability distribution in order to provide the swiftest and most expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncertainty that would affect the outcome of different decision options.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods in finance are often used to evaluate investments in projects at a business unit or corporate level, or other financial valuations.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] They can be used to model project schedules, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall project.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Additionally, they can be used to estimate the financial impact of medical interventions.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in their applications for harassment and domestic abuse restraining orders.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] It was proposed to help women succeed in their petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially reducing the risk of rape and physical assault.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] However, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfectly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The study ran trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of the success level of the proposed program as a whole.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book publications based on book genre in Malaysia.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book's price according to book genre in the local market.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo results were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond of and was used to compare book publications between Malaysia and Japan.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Nassim Nicholas Taleb writes about Monte Carlo generators in his 2001 book *Fooled by Randomness* as a real instance of the reverse Turing test: a human can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart from a generated one.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve various problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also Random number generation) and observing that fraction of the numbers that obeys some property or properties.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The method is useful for obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analytically.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carlo integration.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Deterministic numerical integration algorithms work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when the functions have many variables.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] First, the number of function evaluations needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] For example, if 10 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then 10100 points are needed for 100 dimensions—far too many to be computed.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] This is called the curse of dimensionality.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Second, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an iterated integral.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] 100 dimensions is by no means unusual, since in many physical problems, a "dimension" is equivalent to a degree of freedom.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase in computation time.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] As long as the function in question is reasonably well-behaved, it can be estimated by randomly selecting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of the function values at these points.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] By the central limit theorem, this method displays $\scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}$ convergence—i.e., quadrupling the number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dimensions.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A refinement of this method, known as importance sampling in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more frequently where the integrand is large.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] To do this precisely one would have to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an integral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as stratified sampling, recursive stratified sampling, adaptive umbrella sampling or the VEGAS algorithm.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] A similar approach, the quasi-Monte Carlo method, uses low-discrepancy sequences.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important points more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the integral more quickly.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simulate random walks over it (Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Such methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, Gibbs sampling, Wang and Landau algorithm, and interacting type MCMC methodologies such as the sequential Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in numerical simulation is in numerical optimization.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The problem is to minimize (or maximize) functions of some vector that often has many dimensions.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Many problems can be phrased in this way: for example, a computer chess program could be seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best evaluation function at the end.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In the traveling salesman problem the goal is to minimize distance traveled.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] There are also applications to engineering design, such as multidisciplinary design optimization.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models to solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configuration space.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Reference is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and optimization.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The traveling salesman problem is what is called a conventional optimization problem.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with the lowest total distance.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] If instead of the goal being to minimize the total distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minimize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conventional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jams, time of day, etc.).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Probabilistic formulation of inverse problems leads to the definition of a probability distribution in the model space.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] This probability distribution combines prior information with new information obtained by measuring some observable parameters (data).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is nonlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to describe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood model is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution power of the data is desired.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] In the general case many parameters are modeled, and an inspection of the marginal probability densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of models according to the posterior probability distribution and to analyze and display the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods of model properties is conveyed to the spectator.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] This can be accomplished by means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit formula for the *a priori* distribution is available.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm, can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possibly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex *a priori* information and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.
[src:path-tracing/monte-carlo-method] The method's general philosophy was discussed by Elishakoff and Grüne-Yanoff and Weirich.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracing is used to create photorealistic images for artistic purposes, and for applications such as architectural rendering and product design.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It is also used to render frames for animated films, and visual effects for film and television.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Because it can be very accurate and unbiased, it is commonly used to generate reference images when testing the quality of other rendering algorithms.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The technique uses the Monte Carlo method to compute estimates of global illumination and simulate the ways different materials reflect (or scatter), transmit, absorb, and emit light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It can incorporate simple modeling of the effects of aperture and lens (depth of field, and bokeh) and shutter speed (motion blur), or more realistic simulation of the optical components in a camera.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The algorithm works by describing illumination in a scene using the *rendering equation*, or *light transport equation*, and finding an approximate solution using Monte Carlo integration.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This process is repeated many times for each pixel (each repetition, with generated path and transmitted light, is called a *sample*), and the results are averaged.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] One main difference between this algorithm and standard ray tracing is that a single unbranching path is traced each time, while "Whitted-style" or "Cook-style" ray tracing recursively samples branching paths (e.g. when light is both reflected and refracted by a glass object).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Because path tracing uses random samples there is noise in the final image, which decreases as more samples are taken.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Images commonly require many thousands of samples per pixel (spp) to reduce noise to an acceptable level, and denoising techniques (e.g. based on neural networks) are often used.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Denoising is usually necessary when path tracing is used for real-time rendering in video games, because relatively few samples can be taken.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Many alternative algorithms for path tracing have been developed, although they do not always outperform more straightforward implementations.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] These include bidirectional path tracing (which traces paths forwards from the light source as well as backwards from the camera), Metropolis light transport, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Video games often use biased versions of path tracing to improve performance (e.g. limiting the number of bounces in each path).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A family of techniques called ReSTIR has been developed that can help real-time path tracing by sharing data between nearby pixels and consecutive frames.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Like all ray tracing methods, path tracing is based on ray casting, which Arthur Appel used for computer graphics rendering in the late 1960s.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In 1980, John Turner Whitted published a recursive ray tracing algorithm that allows rendering images of scenes containing mirrored surfaces and refractive transparent objects.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In 1984, Cook et al. described a form of ray tracing called *distributed ray tracing*, which uses Monte Carlo integration to render effects such as depth of field, motion blur, reflection from rough surfaces, and area lights.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The same year, the radiosity method (not a ray tracing method) was published, which was the first physically based method for rendering diffuse global illumination.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In 1986, Jim Kajiya published a paper exploring how to use distributed ray tracing to render physically-based global illumination, and this paper also introduced and named the method called "path tracing".
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracing and other distributed ray tracing techniques were further refined in the late 1980s and early 1990s by researchers such as James Arvo and Peter Shirley, and by Greg Ward in the open source Radiance software.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] To address this, variations of path tracing that trace paths from both the camera and from light sources, called *bidirectional path tracing*, were published in 1993 by Eric Lafortune and Yves Willems, and in 1997 by Eric Veach and Leonidas Guibas.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In 1997 Veach and Guibas also published an alternative method called *Metropolis light transport*, which combines bidirectional path tracing with the Metropolis method.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Veach's lengthy Ph.D. dissertation described both techniques, along with the theoretical background of path tracing; later, the book Physically Based Rendering (which won an Academy Award for Technical Achievement in 2014) helped to make information about path tracing more widely available.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracing requires tracing a large number of *paths* of light in order to produce an image with a visually acceptable amount of noise.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This made path tracing very slow on computers available in the 1980s and 1990s, and noise remained a problem when trying to reproduce the style of earlier computer graphics animated films.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Most animated films produced until around 2010, by studios such as Pixar, used rasterization-based rendering, with ray tracing used selectively for reflections (and later for precomputed or cached global illumination).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] However the speed of computers rapidly increased during the 1990s.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Blue Sky Studios pioneered using Monte Carlo ray tracing for global illumination in animation, including in the 1998 short film "Bunny", but they did not disclose the precise techniques used.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracing gradually become more practical for film production in the early 2000s.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The Arnold renderer, developed by Marcos Fajardo, was used by Sony Pictures Imageworks to produce the feature-length film *Monster House*, released in 2006.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Pixar rewrote their RenderMan software to use path tracing, and released their first feature-length path-traced film *Finding Dory* in 2016.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Although path tracing still had a large computational cost, animation studios discovered that less human labor was required when using it, for example because global illumination no longer needed to be faked by manually placing lights.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The amount of noise present in path traced images still caused difficulties, particularly when rendering motion blur (which was used extensively by earlier animated films) but denoising techniques were developed to address this.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] New techniques were also needed for rendering hair and fur, and to handle the extremely large scenes sometimes required by films.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Renderers such as Arnold, and Disney's Hyperion, originally only used CPUs for rendering, but as GPUs became more capable (and APIs such as CUDA, OpenCL, and OptiX were released) researchers and developers began adapting algorithms and implementations to use GPUs.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] GPUs can dramatically reduce rendering time: for example using a high-end GPU to accelerate portions of the rendering code can make it over 30 times faster than using only a high-end CPU.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Kajiya's 1986 paper defined a recursive integral equation called the rendering equation, which describes a simplified form of *light transport*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This expresses *I(x,x')*, the light arriving at point *x* from point *x'*, as the product of a *geometry term*, *g(x,x')*, which is 0 if there is something blocking the light between the two points and 1 otherwise, and the amount of light leaving point *x'* and traveling towards *x*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The light leaving point *x'* is the sum of the light emitted by the surface at *x'*, and the integral of the light arriving at *x'* from all other points in the scene (the integration domain *S*) and being reflected towards *x*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The equation is often called the *light transport equation* (LTE), and it is frequently written using integration over directions instead of surfaces.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The version of the equation used by Kajiya assumes the light is a single wavelength (wavelength does not appear as a parameter for any of the functions).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It is a simplification for geometrical optics, and does not take into account phenomena such as diffraction, polarization, and fluorescence.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It integrates only over surfaces, and does not handle *participating media* (regions of space that scatter, absorb, and emit light).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] However extensions to handle such cases, and multiple wavelengths, were mentioned in the paper, and were well understood (and there is no fundamental limitation of the path tracing algorithm that prevents rendering these effects).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Kajiya described how older ray tracing methods find approximate solutions to the rendering equation.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] He also showed that the rendering equation is equivalent to the *radiosity equation* solved by the radiosity rendering method; however the radiosity method assumes surfaces are Lambertian, and using it for non-Lambertian materials gives inaccurate (biased) values.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Additional bias is caused by the fact that the radiosity method uses finite element approximations of surfaces.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Kajiya adapted existing distributed ray tracing methods to solve the rendering equation (i.e. to find radiance values at chosen points on surfaces for a steady state or equilibrium solution to light transport in the scene) in an unbiased way, using Monte Carlo integration.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A constant "ambient term" may be added to approximate global illumination.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Distributed ray tracing introduced the use of Monte Carlo integration for rendering rough reflection, sampling multiple directions at each bounce instead of using the contribution of a single direction, but diffuse global illumination was still usually approximated using an ambient term.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The problem with using Monte Carlo integration for diffuse global illumination is the high variance of the result (requiring many samples to reduce noise to an acceptable level).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] To address this, the paper first explored stratified sampling approaches.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Distributed ray tracing allows multiple branching rays to be traced at each step, and a method called "hierarchical integration", using independent stratification of the integration domain at each step, had previously been explored.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] However global illumination requires sampling larger domains of directions or surface points.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Adaptively stratifying these domains in order to reduce variance was found to be too difficult.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Importance sampling, where samples are chosen from a non-uniform distribution according to how much they are likely to contribute to the final result, was identified as a more viable approach.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Ray tracers are often implemented using recursive functions, however a path tracer by nature does not need to be recursive, and can use a loop instead.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Here is pseudocode for a non-recursive function that traces a single path.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It can either use *next event estimation* (NEE) or wait until the path hits a light by chance before accumulating light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The code uses "ray" values that consist of a start point in 3D space and a normalized direction vector.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] When simulating a pinhole camera, the input camera ray should use the camera location as the start point, and a direction chosen based on the pixel location.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The function should be called multiple times for each pixel, using the average of the returned results as the final pixel value.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The `random()` function should return a value between 0 and 1.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] For simplicity, the code only works for opaque surface materials, and it assumes the scene is enclosed (rays can never exit the scene).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It only traces a single wavelength of light, but could be modified to work with RGB values or spectral rendering (see below).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Light sources handled in the non-NEE case are assumed to be perfectly diffuse (otherwise, instead of a constant emittedLight value, another function would need to be evaluated to compute the amount of light emitted in the opposite direction to the ray).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The code uses a trick known as *Russian roulette* to make the function unbiased by terminating the loop probabilistically.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Provided `ComputeTerminationProbability` returns a value greater than 0 (or eventually does, e.g. when `throughput` drops below a threshold) then the loop will eventually terminate (by returning the accumulated value).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Whenever "q" is greater than 0 and the loop keeps going, `throughput` is increased to compensate for the fact that other sampled paths may have been terminated at that point.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This ensures that the result has the correct expected value.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The "q" value can be computed using any heuristic (even a constant probability could be used), but to make it effective, if `throughput` drops to a very low value (close to zero) then q should be close to 1.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] If larger termination probabilities are used, paths will tend to be shorter, but variance will be higher (there will be fewer long paths, but the throughput in those paths will be increased by a larger factor, which will tend to produce scattered bright pixels).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] `CosineWeightedSample` samples directions in the hemisphere at a point on a surface, with probability proportional to the cosine of the angle between the direction and the surface normal (equivalent to integrating using the *projected solid angle* measure).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This is commonly done for diffuse surfaces, and it simplifies the code because the cosine factor in the throughput formula and the inverse probability factor (required for importance sampling) cancel.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Otherwise, direction sampling usually tries to use probabilities proportional to the product of the BRDF and the cosine factor.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] For perfectly specular surfaces, only a single direction is possible and slightly different code must be used.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The BRDF value is multiplied by *π* to cancel out the factor 1/*π* included in the BRDF by convention.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] To improve performance and turn path tracing into a useful algorithm for rendering complex, realistic images, various techniques and enhancements are incorporated into the rendering engine.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Importance sampling is a standard technique to reduce the variance (in this context, average squared magnitude of the error) of the result of Monte Carlo integration.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It can significantly reduce the number of samples required to render a path traced image with an acceptable amount of noise.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It involves choosing a probability density function (PDF) that is roughly proportional to the value being integrated, and drawing samples from that probability density instead of from a uniform distribution.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This is especially effective for glossy or shiny materials.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Importance sampling requires selecting a single probability density function (PDF) from which to draw the samples used for Monte Carlo integration, but often in path tracing, there are multiple alternative PDFs that can be used.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] For example, this can occur when integrating a function that is the product of two other functions, if there are good PDFs known for sampling the two functions individually, but not for sampling the product.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Either one of the PDFs must be chosen, or some method must be found for combining them.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A common case is sampling the amount of direct light from an area light that is reflected by a point on the surface of an object towards the camera.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The first strategy ensures that the sampled ray does not miss the light, but for a glossy surface it may choose a direction at which very little light is reflected towards the camera, so it is more effective for rough (diffuse) surfaces.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The second strategy is often effective for glossy surfaces because it will likely choose a direction at which the value of the BRDF is high, but the ray in the chosen direction may miss the light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In simpler forms of path tracing, usually the first strategy is used for direct light, and is known as *next event estimation* (NEE), and the algorithm then continues tracing the path to sample indirect light, using the second strategy to select the sampled direction.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] If the next ray hits the surface of the light by chance (the light is usually also an object in the scene), the emitted light from the surface is ignored because otherwise that light would be counted twice.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This works well for diffuse surfaces, but is not optimal for glossy surfaces.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A method called *multiple importance sampling* (MIS) allows using both types of sampling together, avoiding situations where a suboptimal strategy is chosen or values are counted twice (causing bias).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] MIS computes weights for blending the two samples so that the result is unbiased, and a larger weight is given to the strategy that is more likely to be effective.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Weights are chosen using a heuristic, and an unbiased result will be produced if the weights satisfy certain conditions.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Although various heuristics have been devised, some of which may be more effective in different situations, the *balance heuristic* is broadly applicable.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A variation called the *one-sample model* selects one sampling strategy to use instead of blending multiple samples, and in this variation the balance heuristic always minimizes variance.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] MIS can be used whenever multiple alternative probability density functions (PDFs) are available to use for importance sampling, and none of the alternatives is clearly better in all situations (some of the PDFs might only partially cover the domain being sampled).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] It is an essential component of bidirectional path tracing (see below).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The basic path tracing algorithm uses a random number generator to choose ray directions to sample at each point in the path (and points on lights, if next event estimation is used).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This ensures that the result is unbiased, and avoids creating visible artifacts in the image.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] However when path tracing is repeated and the samples are averaged, because the sampled directions are completely random, they will not sample the integration domain evenly (there will be clumps and gaps in the directions that are sampled).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This is normal and unavoidable for standard Monte Carlo integration, but there are techniques called *quasi-Monte Carlo* techniques that can reduce the variance by making the samples more evenly distributed.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This means that the samples no longer have the randomness properties required by standard Monte Carlo integration, and so it must be done carefully to avoid bias and artifacts.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The simplest way of doing this is to break the domain being sampled (e.g. the hemisphere of ray directions leaving a surface) into segments and choosing a random point in each segment.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This is called *stratified sampling*, and its drawbacks are that the number of samples being taken must be known in advance, and clumping may still occur (samples from adjacent segments may be very close together if they are both at the edge of a segment).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] If the number of samples is not known in advance, methods called *low-discrepancy sequences* can be used to generate samples that tend to be spread out and cover the domain evenly.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Popular sequences with this property include Halton and Sobol' sequences.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] These are predefined (non-random) sequences, but in modern path tracers the sequences are permuted (*scrambled*) to make them more random.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Stratified sampling and low-discrepancy sequences can become less effective as the dimension of the domain being sampled increases.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracing involves generating very high-dimensional samples.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] E.g. simple path tracing of opaque surfaces (with no light sampling) uses samples that have dimension equal to twice the number of bounces in the path, because each ray direction is a 2D sample on a hemisphere.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] If stratified sampling or a low-discrepancy sequence is used independently for each bounce, there will likely be correlations between the bounce directions, which will cause bias in the image, and also the complete samples (including all bounce directions) will not cover the domain evenly.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracers typically use very high dimensional low discrepancy sequences, but this means that sampling of individual bounces (considered independently as 2D samples) may not be optimal.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A simple technique called *padding* improves this, and a more expensive technique called *sliced optimal transport* generates sequences where all lower-dimensional projections of the multidimensional samples tend to be evenly distributed, by repeatedly optimizing 1D slices.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The above techniques ensure that the set of paths sampled for each individual pixel is well-distributed.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Techniques based on blue noise can help ensure that samples for adjacent pixels tend to be widely separated.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This is usually more important when only a small number of paths is traced per pixel.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Computer graphics commonly represents light values as vectors of red, green, and blue components.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Color or albedo for surfaces is similarly represented as separate multipliers for red, green, and blue.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Although this approach can be adequate in some situations (e.g. it is accurate when light values are added together), when applied to path tracing it is equivalent to simulating a scene lit by exactly three wavelengths of light, which is not realistic.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Modern path tracers provide the option to instead use random samples of wavelengths in the visible spectrum of light, which is called *spectral rendering*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This is now a standard approach when realistic, physically-based rendering is the goal.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] For performance reasons, multiple (e.g. four) wavelengths are usually sampled at a time (a single path is traced, but the lighting calculations are performed for multiple wavelengths).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This can also reduce the *color noise* that occurs with spectral sampling.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Wavelengths are typically converted into RGB values when the path contributions are accumulated.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This approach allows simulating chromatic dispersion (e.g.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] "rainbows" visible when light hits a cut glass object).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] When indirect illumination varies strongly with direction, sampling directions using only the surface material's bidirectional scattering distribution function (BSDF) can be inefficient.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In such cases, *path guiding* builds a representation of the indirect illumination in the scene and uses it to draw samples.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Practical methods can do this iteratively during rendering by learning an approximate spatio-directional radiance field in an unbiased manner.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] To speed this up, path tracers use a 3D spatial data structure.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The structure most commonly used today is the bounding volume hierarchy (BVH), and recent GPUs provide a hardware-accelerated version of this.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] However other structures such as *k*-d trees and octrees have also been used.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Some path tracers require that all objects be represented using triangle meshes, which simplifies code and data structures (hardware acceleration is also usually optimized for triangles).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Generating samples of direct light (for *next event estimation*) is most effective if importance sampling is used, which requires sampling lights proportionally to their brightness, and (ideally) inversely proportionally to the square of the distance to the light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] When the scene has a large number of lights, it becomes prohibitively expensive to examine all lights and compute weights before choosing a small number of lights to sample.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] If path tracing only uses camera rays corresponding to the exact centers of pixels in the image, severe aliasing can result.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracers usually remove or reduce aliasing by filtering out frequencies higher than can be represented by the image's resolution.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] To do this, they use a filter kernel, such as a Gaussian filter, or filters such as Mitchell–Netravali filters or the Lanczos filter that improve sharpness but can introduce ringing artifacts.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The latter approach can reduce variance slightly, but may not be compatible with denoisers (for example, the occasional very bright samples called "fireflies" are spread across a neighborhood of pixels, and cannot be easily removed).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Even when thousands of paths are averaged, the output of path tracing usually contains visible noise.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Although the most reliable (and unbiased) way to reduce noise is to trace more paths (or make improvements such as better importance sampling), many biased approaches have been used to eliminate or reduce noise.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Although technically these bright samples are necessary in order to produce an unbiased image, they are subjectively unhelpful, and they can greatly increase variance.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Many heuristics have been used to identify fireflies and remove them, e.g. replacing them with the average of surrounding pixels or spreading their brightness out to nearby pixels.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This is similar to outlier detection in statistics.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Sometimes individual samples are filtered, rather than accumulated pixel values.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Techniques related to density estimation, using variable-width kernels, have been tried.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Many techniques use edge detection to allow denoising filters that blur the image while still preserving sharp edges of objects.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Edge detection for denoising a rendered image typically uses data other than the final brightness, such as the depth and normal vector of the first point intersected by the camera ray.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Edge-preserving filters that do not rely on this type of data (using only pixel color and brightness values) include *bilateral filters*, *guided filters*, and *non-local means* filters.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Techniques based on wavelets and other multiscale filters have been tried, which can handle the varying frequency characteristics of an image (e.g. blurriness caused by depth of field).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Sometimes the direct light and indirect light contributions to a pixel are rendered and denoised separately, which allows preserving detail in the direct lighting, while smoothing the indirect light (which is usually noisier).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] More complex algorithms denoise specular reflection separately (since it varies differently with pixel location), and some work with individual samples and construct a statistical model for the local light field around each visible point on a surface.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] More recently, convolutional neural networks have been used to implement denoising filters, training the neural network on a large dataset of noisy and noiseless copies of the same images.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] These neural networks can use data such as depth and normal, surface albedo, and surface roughness/shininess as part of their inputs.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] An alternative or complementary approach is *adaptive sampling*, which takes additional samples in regions of the image where variance is higher (this is tricky to do without introducing bias).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The output of path tracing is linear brightness values for pixels, which then need to be converted into a viewable image or a video or film frame.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The range of brightness values may be larger than displayable by a standard computer monitor, or representable by a file format that uses 8-bit color values, such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Images often contain very bright highlights, or pixels where a light source such as the sun is seen directly.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] If the brightness of the entire image is reduced so that the brightest pixels are not clipped, the rest of the scene will often be too dark.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The aim is usually to produce a subjective impression of the true brightness of the scene, despite the reduced range of pixel values.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Many different methods and tone mapping curves are available, often with parameters to tune them.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Some methods aim to reproduce the look of images captured on photographic film, and may alter the colors and saturation of the image.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Tone mapping does not need to be implemented as part of the path tracer.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] If the rendered image is output to a linear HDR format (e.g.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] OpenEXR), tone mapping can be applied later (which may be preferable, since the tone mapping method or parameters can be changed without re-rendering the image).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Real objects are never perfectly smooth mirrors (although perfect mirrors are often simulated in computer graphics for convenience and simplicity).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] When light hits an opaque object, it is always reflected (or *scattered*) in multiple directions.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The amount of light that is reflected in each direction mainly depends on the angle at which it arrives relative to the *surface normal*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Shiny materials, often called *specular* materials, reflect more light at angles close to the angle at which a perfect mirror would reflect light, producing a distinct highlight (called a *specular highlight*) when a bright light source is reflected.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In contrast, materials that scatter light more (reflecting it in a broader range of directions without a sharp peak) are called *rough* or *diffuse*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In general there is no clear distinction between specular and diffuse materials, for example a diffuse surface may have a coat of varnish over it that gives it specular highlights.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Materials for which the amount of light reflected in a particular direction depends only on the angles between the incoming ray of light (called the *incident* ray), the outgoing or reflected ray (called *exitant*), and the surface normal are called *isotropic*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In this case the surface material has no particular orientation (rotating the surface around the surface normal will not change the way light is reflected).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Materials for which the orientation does matter are called *anisotropic*, and include materials such as brushed steel or aluminum.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Although many real-world materials are subtly anisotropic, anisotropy is often ignored by computer graphics, since it is simpler and more efficient to treat materials as isotropic.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] One extreme case is a "perfectly rough" material where the amount of reflected light does not depend on the angle of the incident light, and there are no highlights at all.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] An example of this type of material is the Lambertian material commonly used in computer graphics (it does not exist in the real world, but a material called Spectralon, which is a polymer powder, is very close).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] For a Lambertian material, the amount of reflected light is proportional to the cosine of the angle between the exitant ray and the surface normal.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The above effects can all be described by a type of function called a *bidirectional reflectance distribution function* (BRDF).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The parameters to these functions are the directions of the incoming ray and the outgoing ray with respect to some frame of reference on the surface (there are multiple ways of representing the directions as numbers).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The output of the function is a factor that the amount of incoming light should be multiplied by to get the amount of outgoing light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The BRDF, as typically defined, does not include the factor for Lambertian refectance mentioned above (the cosine of the angle between the exitant ray and the surface normal) and so the BRDF for a Lambertian surface is a constant function.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Omitting this factor gives the BRDF the property of *reciprocity*: swapping the incident and exitant rays in the parameters to the function does not change the output (by convention, both directions point away from the surface).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The BRDF is scaled appropriately for use in the light transport equations (where it is multiplied by incoming light values and integrated), and it returns a value of 1/*π* for a Lambertian material that does not absorb any light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Along with reciprocity, an important property of valid BRDFs is that they are energy conserving: when the BRDF is used in light transport equations, the total amount of light reflected should never be greater than the amount of light arriving at the surface.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] (These properties will not hold for individual wavelengths when effects such as fluorescence are observed.) The BRDF must also always return a non-negative value.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] BRDFs can be different for each wavelength of light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] For example non-metallic materials usually have white highlights, reflecting all wavelengths nearly equally at certain angles, while also diffusely reflecting light in a wavelength-dependent way (which gives the material its color).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Wavelength-varying BRDFs can also model iridescent materials.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] BRDFs are a core part of path tracing: they are evaluated at every path vertex where a ray intersects a surface (in order to compute the throughput of the remaining part of the path), and also when computing direct lighting at surface points.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] BRDFs do not describe properties of transparent or partially transparent materials (for which other types of scattering distribution functions are needed).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] However BRDFs are useful because many materials are effectively opaque to visible light, or have a very small amount of translucency near the surface that can be ignored or approximated by the BRDF.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] They often have parameters such as "roughness" that can be easily changed.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Multiple simple BRDFs (often called *lobes* due to the shape of the functions) are sometimes layered.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] BRDFs do not, by themselves, include information about the texture of a surface.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In realistic rendering, often color and "roughness" parameters (and sometimes orientation and amount of anisotropy) are encoded using texture mapping and used to modify the BRDF for individual points on the surface.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A similar type of function used when light passes through the surface of a transparent material is a *bidirectional transmittance distribution function* (BTDF).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] A term that includes both BRDFs and BTDFs is *bidirectional scattering distribution function* (BSDF).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] To handle general scattering in transparent materials, volume rendering uses a similar function (but with an incompatible definition) called a *phase function*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Volumetric path tracing is used for rendering scenes containing *participating media*, which are 3D regions of space (rather than the surfaces of objects) that emit light, or in which light can be absorbed or scattered.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Participating media are often thought of as containing particles, so that a ray of light passing through the medium has a chance of interacting with a particle (and being absorbed or scattered) that is higher the farther the ray travels.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Path tracers that perform volume rendering usually allow it to be combined with rendering of surfaces.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Volumetric path tracing is commonly performed backwards from the camera, like standard path tracing, taking advantage of the reciprocity property of most light interactions.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Camera rays are sampled (or ray directions for reflections or global illumination that arrives at a point on a surface) as usual, and then scattering events are generated when a ray passes through a participating medium that can scatter light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The probability of these scattering events (and how far the ray usually travels before the next event) is related to the density of the material.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] When a ray is scattered, a new ray is cast in the new direction, similar to scattering from a surface, with the probability of each new direction determined by a probability density function called a *phase function*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] All of these operations are much simpler and faster if the participating medium is homogeneous (has the same density everywhere with respect to scattering, absorption, and emission).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] In that case integration can be performed analytically to compute attenuation and emission, and there is also a simpler way to generate scattering events with the correct probability distribution.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] Materials typically rendered as homogeneous media (which may still have complex shapes) include water and colored glass.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The formula used for homogeneous absorption is known as the Beer–Lambert law or Beer's law.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] When the participating medium is inhomogenous (has density or other properties that vary spatially) more complex and slower algorithms must be used.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] These types of media include clouds, mist, smoke, and fire.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The input data for rendering these materials is usually volumetric data (structured similarly to voxels).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] To perform operations such as integration, the code often needs to ray march through the media, querying data for points along the ray.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] This can be done sparsely (examining the material at only a few, usually randomly chosen, points) or densely (examining closely spaced points), depending on the algorithm.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p01] The commonly used *null scattering* algorithm treats the medium as homogeneous when choosing which points to sample, allowing it to sample the medium sparsely, and it can be very efficient if the medium is nearly homogeneous.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] In both cases, a technique called *next event estimation* can be used to reduce variance.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This works by directly sampling an important feature (the camera in the case of *light tracing*, or a light source in the case of *backwards path tracing*) instead of waiting for a path to hit it by chance.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This technique is usually effective, but becomes less useful when specular or near-specular BRDFs are present.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] For *backwards path tracing*, this creates high variance for caustic paths that interact with a diffuse surface, then bounce off a specular surface before hitting a light source.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] *Next event estimation* cannot be used to sample these paths directly from the diffuse surface, because the specular interaction is in the middle.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Likewise, it cannot be used to sample paths from the specular surface because there is only one direction that the light can bounce.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] *Light tracing* has a similar issue when paths interact with a specular surface before hitting the camera.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Because this situation is significantly more common, and noisy (or completely black) glass objects are very visually disruptive, *backwards path tracing* is the only method that is used for unidirectional path tracing in practice.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Bidirectional path tracing provides an algorithm that combines the two approaches and can produce lower variance than either method alone.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] For each sample, two paths are traced independently: one from the light source and one from the camera.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This produces a set of possible sampling strategies, where every vertex of one path can be connected directly to every vertex of the other.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The original *light tracing* and *backwards path tracing* algorithms are both special cases of these strategies.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] For *light tracing*, it is connecting the vertices of the camera path directly to the first vertex of the light path.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] For *backwards path tracing*, it is connecting the vertices of the light path to the first vertex of the camera path.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] In addition, there are several completely new sampling strategies, where intermediate vertices are connected.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Weighting all of these sampling strategies using multiple importance sampling creates a new sampler that can converge faster than unidirectional path tracing, even though more work is required for each sample.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This works particularly well for caustics or scenes that are lit primarily through indirect lighting.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Importance sampling can be used to improve the efficiency of Monte Carlo integration by using a sample distribution that is roughly proportional to the value being integrated.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] However this only works if a good distribution is known, and there is a practical way to draw samples from it.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The sample distributions used in path tracing are often far from optimal, especially if rays starting from the camera must reflect or refract in order to reach the light.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] An alternative way to perform MC integration, the Metropolis method, uses a random walk to generate samples with an improved distribution.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] In standard importance sampling, samples are generated independently, e.g. by sampling ray directions and points on area lights inside a path tracing function that takes a list of random numbers as input (or uses successive calls to a pseudorandom number generator).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] With the Metropolis method, samples (called *proposals*) are instead generated from other samples by modifying them randomly.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] In the context of MLT, the samples are complete paths from the camera to the light source, and the proposals are called *mutations* (of paths).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The main benefit of the algorithm comes from being able to generate new paths that are "close" to existing paths, so they are likely to be good paths for importance sampling if the original path was good.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] A *target function* (typically the luminance of the light contributed to the image by a given path) is used to guide sampling.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Paths (proposals) that are chosen are said to be *accepted*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Paths for which the target function is higher are more likely to be accepted, and paths that are invalid (e.g. some edge in the path is blocked by another object) are never accepted.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] MLT allows generated paths to "wander" all over the image, contributing to any pixel (similar to the paths used for caustics in bidirectional path tracing).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] MLT needs to generate an initial unbiased sample to use as a "seed" path before it can start generating mutations.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This is usually done by resampling, generating (weighted) samples with a distribution proportional to the target function.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] New seed paths are used every certain number of mutations to help ensure that the entire path space is sampled adequately.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The original algorithm selected seed paths from sets of paths generated by bidirectional path tracing.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Because MLT, as originally proposed, generates paths in a very different way than standard path tracing (including bidirectional path tracing) it can be difficult to add MLT to existing path tracers, or incorporate it as part of a path tracer that performs multiple types of path tracing.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The sequence of random numbers, usually numbers in the interval [0, 1), used to generate a particular individual sample is a representation of the sample in a domain called *primary sample space*.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Path tracing can be viewed as Monte Carlo integration using uniform sampling in this sample space (instead of using importance sampling in path space).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Since path tracers typically already provide multiple ways to generate these random numbers, it is usually possible to allow generation of the numbers to be driven by Metropolis method.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This allows an implementation of MLT to use standard path tracing code to evaluate the samples, greatly reducing the amount of new code that needs to be written.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Mutated paths can be generated by modifying the random numbers slightly, rather than performing complex operations on paths.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Because the transition probabilities from path to path in PSSMLT are usually symmetrical (probability is the same in both directions), the calculations are much simpler.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] However PSSMLT is often much less effective than traditional MTL because it cannot usually mutate a small part of the path and keep the rest (which greatly improves efficiency for exploring long paths in MLT).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Instead of the five specialized mutation types used by traditional MLT (e.g. adding or removing one or more path vertices in the middle of a path) it usually just uses large and small steps that modify all of the numbers.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Path tracing has difficulty rendering caustics – bright patches of light that appear when a small or highly directional light source (such as the sun) is reflected or refracted by a shiny surface or transparent object before illuminating another surface.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The result is usually very noisy, with many "fireflies" (stray bright pixels), or caustics may simply be missing.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Bidirectional path tracing can render caustics if light subpaths are allowed to contribute to any pixel in the image (breaking the pixel-by-pixel rendering model), but caustics may still be missing if viewed in a mirror.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This type of difficult lighting can also cause noise elsewhere in the image.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] A different rendering technique called *photon mapping* or *photon density estimation* is able to render caustics more effectively.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Photon mapping works like the "forward" or "particle tracing" portion of bidirectional path tracing, simulating the paths of many "packets" of light emitted by a light source.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] These are called *photons* in the algorithm, but they usually do not actually represent physical photons.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Photons are traced through reflections and refractions until they hit a diffuse (matte) surface or leave the scene.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Information about photons that hit a surface is accumulated in a data structure called a *photon map* and used later, rather than being used immediately for rendering a particular pixel.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The photon map is implemented using a spatial structure such as a *k*-d tree or hash grid.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Photon mapping is biased, because it uses a density estimation filter to smooth out the data and allow estimating the intensity of light at an arbitrary point on a surface.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] If an insufficient number of light samples is used, the image may have a blurry or blotchy appearance caused by the filter.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] One early variation of photon mapping used a photon map to "guide" rays for global illumination (which was rendered using distribution ray tracing), instead of using the radiance information in the map directly.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This is similar to *path guiding* in modern path tracing.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Another method explored was the use of data from photon maps as control variates for reducing the variance of path tracing.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Both of these approaches can be unbiased.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] An algorithm called *progressive photon mapping* is optimized to allow tracing a larger number of photons, with the number not limited by available memory.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Rather than beginning with photon mapping, it starts with a "camera pass", in which paths are traced from the camera until they hit a diffuse surface.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Information about these subpaths (called *visible points*) is stored in a spatial data structure.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] In the photon mapping pass, subpaths from the light source are traced until they hit a diffuse surface, and any nearby subpaths from the camera pass are then found.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The camera subpaths determine how much light from the light subpath is added to each pixel in the image.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Instead of consuming memory by storing photons (light subpaths) in a *k*-d tree (or other spatial structure), progressive photon mapping stores visible points (camera subpaths), which is still a problem because a path traced image usually requires a large number of camera rays for each pixel.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] A variation called *stochastic progressive photon mapping* makes the algorithm more practical by breaking rendering into multiple pairs of camera and light passes, storing typically only a single camera subpath for each pixel at a time.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The algorithm also tracks the number of nearby photons found for each pixel's visible points, and reduces the size of the filter kernel in subsequent passes, which allows rendering sharp caustics even though the photons are traced in smaller batches.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] One problem with photon mapping approaches is that surfaces must usually be divided into specular (glossy) and diffuse surfaces, with different strategies used for each, and this classification may not always be optimal.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Later techniques called *vertex connection and merging* (VCM) and *unified path sampling* (UPS) create frameworks that allow using both photon mapping and standard path tracing on any surface, and attempt to reduce bias further.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The unified frameworks are forms of bidirectional path tracing (BDPT), based on combining paths generated by different strategies.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The same path can potentially be generated by multiple strategies, and so paths must be blended carefully, using multiple importance sampling (MIS) weights.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Because the sampling probabilities of all types of paths can be computed (whether or not they use the photon mapping strategy), they can be blended using MIS weights, as in standard BDPT.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The algorithm is still biased but will converge to the correct result faster than other forms of photon mapping as the number of light subpaths increases.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Reusing the same light subpath for multiple pixels (as is done in most forms of photon mapping) can cause correlations between nearby pixels, which may produce visible artifacts and cause problems for denoisers.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The VCM method reduces this correlation by randomly modifying each light subpath before using it.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Improvements to GPU performance and ray tracing acceleration have enabled the widespread use of ray tracing in video games, but in order to render realistic lighting in scenes lit by large numbers of lights, and diffuse global illumination with many bounces, many rays must be cast.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This is challenging to do in real time at an acceptable frame rate, especially when rendering large, detailed environments (in particular, unbiased path tracing, with arbitrary path lengths, is usually not practical in real time).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] One approach to address this is to share data between pixels in the image, or between consecutive frames, so fewer ray casts need to be performed per pixel.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This is commonly done by denoisers and temporal anti-aliasing (which both enable using fewer samples per pixel), however they can cause blurring of the image, "ghosting" artifacts across frames, light leakage around corners, and other types of bias.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Reuse algorithms based on precomputation and caching may not respond quickly enough to lighting changes during real-time rendering, and may cause significant bias.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] A family of techniques called *spatiotemporal reservoir resampling*, or *ReSTIR*, allows sharing of samples between nearby pixels, and carrying samples forward to the next frame even when objects or the camera have moved.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] It can do this without introducing bias, or it can be used in biased modes that have better performance and less noise.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] ReSTIR uses a form of weighted reservoir sampling, maintaining a data structure called a *reservoir* for each pixel.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The reservoir stores a single sample along with a weight similar to the weights used in importance sampling.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] (Reservoirs storing more than one sample can also be used: the original ReSTIR implementation used 4 samples per reservoir for its biased version but only 1 sample for the more expensive unbiased version).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The earliest form of ReSTIR, now called ReSTIR DI, is designed for direct lighting in scenes with many lights.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] To generate initial samples, it uses an older technique called *resampled importance sampling* (RIS).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] It take many samples of lights cheaply (without considering visibility) and chooses one based on how bright the samples are (this is an approximate or stochastic form of importance sampling).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The chosen sample (e.g. a point on a specific light) is then tested to determine if it is visible (if not, it can be treated as a light sample with zero brightness) and is stored in the reservoir, along with a weight.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] During spatial reuse steps, another pixel is chosen randomly from a *neighborhood* around the target pixel (e.g. all pixels with distance less than 30 pixels away).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The sample in this other pixel's reservoir is then merged into the target pixel's reservoir by computing multiple importance sampling (MIS) weights for the two samples and choosing a sample using probabilities proportional to the weights (a similar procedure to RIS).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The weight in the reservoir is updated whether or not the other pixel's sample was chosen.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Some implementations examine multiple neighboring pixels (e.g.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] 4 neighbors) and choose one, which helps reduce variance but is more expensive, requiring tracing more rays.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Temporal reuse, reusing samples from a corresponding pixel in the previous frame, is implemented in a similar way to spatial reuse.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Because the camera and objects in the scene may have moved and lighting may have changed, visibility and brightness of both light samples at the surface point in both frames needs to be computed in order to calculate the correct weights, again usually requiring tracing two additional rays.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] By combining the steps in this way, samples can quickly propagate to neighboring pixels allowing a large amount of potential reuse of any "good" samples that are found.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This can be helpful in difficult lighting situations (e.g. when there are many lights but most of them are shadowed) however excessive reuse of a small number of samples causes correlation artifacts that can be very visible.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Path tracing can use the unbiased version of ReSTIR DI to compute direct light for the first surface point intersected by the camera ray.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] A more general version of ReSTIR for path tracing, called ReSTIR PT, extends the algorithm to support reusing arbitrary paths instead of just direct light samples.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] This involves applying a *shift mapping* transformation to a sample to make it applicable to the position and surface orientation needed by a different pixel or a different frame (shift mappings were introduced as part of gradient domain rendering).
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] For example a shift mapping called the *reconnection shift* makes it possible to reuse the portion of a path after the second surface intersection, only needing to trace one ray to check visibility between the first and second intersections.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] The reconnection shift is very effective for diffuse global illumination, and is the basis of a simplified algorithm called ReSTIR GI (which assumes all surfaces are Lambertian at the second intersection) that has been used in games.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] ReSTIR is primarily intended for real-time rendering, but it can also be used to speed up offline rendering.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] To mitigate these problems, the temporal reuse portion can be omitted, and instead initial sampling and spatial reuse are repeated multiple times and the results are averaged.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Many variations of ReSTIR now exist, applying the technique to volume rendering, and to depth of field and motion blur effects, and combining it with other techniques such as path guiding.
[src:path-tracing/path-tracing-p02] Although most forms of ReSTIR work in *screen space* (with a reservoir for each pixel) there also exist *world space* versions that use RIS and spatiotemporal reuse to find good light samples for regions of space in a 3D grid.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] In computer graphics, the **rendering equation** is an integral equation that expresses the amount of light leaving a point on a surface as the sum of emitted light and reflected light.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] It was independently introduced into computer graphics by David Immel et al. and James Kajiya in 1986.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] The equation is important in the theory of physically based rendering, describing the relationships between the bidirectional reflectance distribution function (BRDF) and the radiometric quantities used in rendering.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] The rendering equation is defined at every point on every surface in the scene being rendered, including points hidden from the camera.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] The incoming light quantities on the right side of the equation usually come from the left (outgoing) side at other points in the scene (ray casting can be used to find these other points).
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] The radiosity rendering method solves a discrete approximation of this system of equations.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] In distributed ray tracing, the integral on the right side of the equation may be evaluated using Monte Carlo integration by randomly sampling possible incoming light directions.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] Path tracing improves and simplifies this method.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] The rendering equation can be extended to handle effects such as fluorescence (in which some absorbed energy is re-emitted at different wavelengths) and can support transparent and translucent materials by using a bidirectional scattering distribution function (BSDF) in place of a BRDF.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] The theory of path tracing sometimes uses a *path integral* (integral over possible paths from a light source to a point) instead of the integral over possible incoming directions.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] Two noteworthy features are: its linearity—it is composed only of multiplications and additions, and its spatial homogeneity—it is the same in all positions and orientations.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] These mean a wide range of factorings and rearrangements of the equation are possible.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] It is a Fredholm integral equation of the second kind, similar to those that arise in quantum field theory.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] Note this equation's spectral and time dependence — $L_{\text{o}}$ may be sampled at or integrated over sections of the visible spectrum to obtain, for example, a trichromatic color sample.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] A pixel value for a single frame in an animation may be obtained by fixing $t;$ motion blur can be produced by averaging $L_{\text{o}}$ over some given time interval (by integrating over the time interval and dividing by the length of the interval).
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] Note that a solution to the rendering equation is the function $L_{\text{o}}$ .
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] The function $L_{\text{i}}$ is related to $L_{\text{o}}$ via a ray-tracing operation: The incoming radiance from some direction at one point is the outgoing radiance at some other point in the opposite direction.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] Solving the rendering equation for any given scene is the primary challenge in realistic rendering.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] One approach to solving the equation is based on finite element methods, leading to the radiosity algorithm.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] Another approach using Monte Carlo methods has led to many different algorithms including path tracing, photon mapping, and Metropolis light transport, among others.
[src:path-tracing/rendering-equation] Although the equation is very general, it does not capture every aspect of light reflection.
